english:
  title: Letter of Thanks to Chancellor Choe Jong-jun for a Banquet on the Year the Capital Was Moved
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I bow respectfully and present this to Your Excellency the Chancellor.

    I was honored by your gracious summons to attend the splendid banquet yesterday. Night had fallen by the time I stumbled home, carried away by wine. The gratitude I feel is etched deep within my heart. Yet I cannot recall what foolish words escaped my lips in my drunkenness—has this old madness of mine erupted once more?

    Since we moved from the old capital, the great families have been in such haste that none have had time to properly age their wine. Fine spirits are rare indeed, and exceptional ones remain but a dream. Yet the wine Your Excellency bestowed yesterday was so crisp and exquisite that I would not dare compare it to wine aged nine times over a hundred days. How could one who has never cultivated a taste for drinking hope to remain sober when given such wine to drink?

    As for the music—this is not merely unheard of in this place. Since my exile came upon me these past years, I have not heard even a single note from a solitary string or flute. My heart has been shrouded in gloom with no solace. Yet suddenly, the voices rose in song, the pipes and flutes sang out in harmonious symphony like water boiling in a cauldron. Can any man, even one as cold and bookish as I, possess a heart of wood and stone? How could I not delight in it?

    Each instrument was of extraordinary quality, and the musicians summoned were all masters of our time. How could such melody not seep into one's ears and intoxicate one's very bones? As for myself, though I have never mastered music, my nature has always loved to listen. When the music played, my shoulders swayed without my knowing—how ridiculous I must have appeared!

    Your Excellency offered to my unaccustomed palate flavors never before tasted, and to my eager ears the sounds of purest joy. Through such kindness, you granted me a night of unparalleled pleasure—a joy I have never known in all my years. I cannot imagine such a day will come again. Yet how can I repay such generosity? I can only offer daily prayers for your long life.

    The wine has not yet left my head; my mind still swims and my hand trembles. These words are written hastily and poorly. My gratitude knows no bounds, and I am overwhelmed with reverence.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The old capital likely refers to Gaeseong; the poem is written upon the occasion of the capital's move to a new location.
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Kyu-bo had suffered exile and banishment before this period, making his joy at being invited to court and hearing music again particularly poignant.
  - key: ''
    value: The formal drunken apologies and self-deprecation are typical features of thank-you letters from this era, expressing both gratitude and humility.
